  "questions": [
    {
      "qnum": 1,
      "marks": 3,
      "answer": "a b c (abc)\n6 1 3 (18)\n4 2 4 (32)\n2 3 5 (30)\nAll products are even, hence the product of a, b and c is even.",
      "markAllocation": [
        {
          "code": "B1",
          "type": "B",
          "value": 1,
          "criterion": "Any one correct row for b = 1, b = 2 or b = 3. Products do not need to be found for this mark."
        },
        {
          "code": "M1",
          "type": "M",
          "value": 1,
          "criterion": "Attempts the product abc for at least 2 valid combinations."
        },
        {
          "code": "A1",
          "type": "A",
          "value": 1,
          "criterion": "Finds all three valid combinations with correct products seen and somewhere/shows why this is exhaustive and concludes. *"
        }
      ],
      "guidance": "Numerical approach using the table:\nB1: Any one correct row for b = 1, b = 2 or b = 3. Products do not need to be found for this mark.\nM1: Attempts the product abc for at least 2 valid combinations.\nA1*: Requires:\n• All three valid combinations with correct products\n• No other combinations shown unless they are crossed out or e.g. have a cross at the end of the row or are discounted in some way\n• A (minimal) conclusion e.g. the product of a, b and c is even, hence proven, QED, hence it is even, each product stated as even, etc.\nAlgebraic/logic approach:\nB1: Uses the information to obtain a correct equation connecting a and b e.g. $a + 2b = 8$, $a = 8 - 2b$\nM1: States a must be even and considers the product abc in some way\nA1*: States e.g. abc is even with a reason e.g. “even $\\times$ anything is even”\nPure Algebraic approach:\nB1: Uses the information to obtain a correct equation connecting a and b e.g. $a + 2b = 8$, $a = 8 - 2b$\nM1: Attempts the product of a, b and c in terms of b (or some other letter) $(8-2b)b(b+2)$\nA1*: Concludes abc is even and makes a (minimal) conclusion. There must be no algebraic errors. $(8-2b)b(b+2) = 2(4-b)b(b+2)$ which is even, hence proven, QED etc.\nNB using this approach “$abc = -2b^3 + 4b^2 + 16b$ which is even hence proven” is not sufficient – they would need to say e.g. which is even + even + even or factor out the 2."
    },
    {
      "qnum": 2,
      "marks": 7,
      "parts": [
        {
          "label": "(a)",
          "marks": 2,
          "answer": "$k=\\frac{2}{5}$",
          "markAllocation": [
            {
              "code": "M1",
              "type": "M",
              "value": 1,
              "criterion": "Substitutes $x=\\frac{4}{5}$ into $f(x)$, equates to $\\frac{243}{32}$ and attempts to make k the subject by taking the 5th root of both sides."
            },
            {
              "code": "A1",
              "type": "A",
              "value": 1,
              "criterion": "$k=\\frac{2}{5}$ with no errors and sufficient working shown. *"
            }
          ],
          "guidance": "Accept as a minimum $(2-\\frac{4k}{5})^5 = \\frac{243}{32} \\Rightarrow (2-\\frac{4k}{5}) = \\frac{3}{2} \\Rightarrow k=\\frac{2}{5}$. Note that just $(2-\\frac{4k}{5})^5 = \\frac{243}{32} \\Rightarrow k=\\frac{2}{5}$ scores no marks as the minimum for the M mark requires taking the 5th root of both sides.\nAlternative by verification:\nM1: Substitutes $k=\\frac{2}{5}$ and $x=\\frac{4}{5}$ and attempts to raise an evaluated $2-kx$ to the power of 5.\nA1: Fully correct work and makes a (minimal) conclusion e.g. Hence proven, QED, Therefore true, etc. Note that just $(2-\\frac{2}{5} \\times \\frac{4}{5})^5 = \\frac{243}{32}$ or $(2-\\frac{8}{25})^5 = (\\frac{42}{25})^5$ scores no marks as the $2-k \\times \\frac{4}{5}$ or $2-\\frac{8}{25}$ must be evaluated for the M mark."
        },
        {
          "label": "(b)",
          "marks": 3,
          "answer": "$32 - \\frac{64}{5}x + \\frac{32}{5}x^2$",
          "markAllocation": [
            {
              "code": "M1",
              "type": "M",
              "value": 1,
              "criterion": "Attempts the binomial expansion to obtain the correct structure for the x or $x^2$ term i.e. the correct binomial coefficient with the correct power of 2 and the correct power of $\\pm \\frac{2}{5}x$. The binomial coefficients do not have to be evaluated but must be correct if they are. If awarding this mark for the $x^2$ term you can condone missing brackets e.g. $^5C_2 \\times 2^3 \\times (\\pm \\frac{2}{5}x)^2$."
            },
            {
              "code": "A1",
              "type": "A",
              "value": 1,
              "criterion": "For the correct simplified x or $x^2$ term i.e. $-\\frac{64}{5}x$ or $+\\frac{32}{5}x^2$."
            },
            {
              "code": "A1",
              "type": "A",
              "value": 1,
              "criterion": "For $32 - \\frac{64}{5}x + \\frac{32}{5}x^2$ which may be written as a list. Allow equivalents for $\\frac{64}{5}$ e.g. 12.8. Condone $(32 + (-\\frac{64}{5}x) + \\frac{32}{5}x^2)$. Ignore any extra terms but do not isw – mark their final answer. If they don’t simplify in (b) do not allow simplified terms in (c) as recovery."
            }
          ],
          "guidance": "Alternative takes out a power of 2: $(2-\\frac{2}{5}x)^5 = 2^5(1-\\frac{1}{5}x)^5 = 32(1+5(-\\frac{1}{5}x) + \\frac{5 \\times 4}{2}(-\\frac{1}{5}x)^2 + ...) = 32(1-x+\\frac{2}{5}x^2+...)$. Score M1 for $32(1 \\pm 5 \\times (\\pm \\frac{1}{5}x) + ...)$ or $32(1 \\pm \\frac{5 \\times 4}{2} \\times (\\pm \\frac{1}{5}x)^2 + ...)$ condoning $(\\pm \\frac{1}{5}x)^2$ as above. Then A marks as above."
        },
        {
          "label": "(c)",
          "marks": 2,
          "answer": "$f'(0) = -32$",
          "markAllocation": [
            {
              "code": "M1",
              "type": "M",
              "value": 1,
              "criterion": "Attempts to differentiate their expansion and substitutes $x=0$ which may be implied. For the differentiation, look for $x^n \\rightarrow x^{n-1}$ at least once including $k \\rightarrow 0$ or $kx \\rightarrow k$."
            },
            {
              "code": "A1",
              "type": "A",
              "value": 1,
              "criterion": "$-32$ following correct differentiation. Or follow through on their q provided the expansion in (b) was of the form $p+qx+rx^2$, $p,q,r \\ne 0$ and the differentiation is correct for their $p+qx+rx^2$ i.e. $q+2rx$."
            }
          ],
          "guidance": "In part (c) you can also ignore any extra terms e.g. do not penalise if they have differentiated any of the extra terms incorrectly in an otherwise correct solution."
        }
      ]
